INSERT INTO `mosques_mosque` VALUES (2,'جامع الـجزائر','الـجزائر','الحراش','','المحمدية، الحراش، الجزائر العاصمة',36.73513000,3.14023000,'','',1,'2026-01-24 21:34:07.510416','2026-02-09 18:54:49.522172',1,NULL,NULL,1,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,''),(3,'La grande Mosquée de Paris','France','Paris','','2bis Pl. du Puits de l'Ermite. 75005',48.84225000,2.35505000,'','',1,'2026-01-26 19:36:47.341623','2026-01-31 22:26:55.789220',NULL,NULL,NULL,2,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,''),(4,'La mosquée Bleue','Turquie','Istanboul','','Cankurtaran, At Meydanı Cd No:7, 34122 Fatih/İstanbul, Turquie',41.00557000,28.97677000,'','',1,'2026-01-27 18:07:10.575138','2026-01-31 22:26:34.121359',NULL,NULL,NULL,183,NULL,NULL,'',NULL,NULL,''),(9,'الْمَسْجِدُ ٱلْحَرَام','السعودية','مكة المكرمة','','Al Haram, Makkah 24231',21.25190000,39.49340000,'The Grand Mosque (Masjid al-Haram) is the holiest mosque in Islam, located in the heart of Mecca, in western Saudi Arabia. At its center stands the Kaaba, which, according to Islamic belief, is the first house of worship built for humanity on Earth. This is the most sacred and revered place on Earth for Muslims. The Grand Mosque is the direction Muslims face in prayer (qibla), and it is the destination of the Hajj pilgrimage. It is called the Grand Mosque because fighting within its precincts has been forbidden since the Prophet Muhammad's triumphant entry into Mecca. Muslims believe that a single prayer performed there is equivalent to one hundred thousand prayers elsewhere.','The Construction of the KaabarnrnThe history of the mosque begins with the construction of the Holy Kaaba. It was first built by angels before Adam (peace be upon him), and it was made of red ruby. This structure was then raised to heaven during the Flood. After the Flood, the Prophet Abraham and his son Ishmael (peace be upon them both) rebuilt the Kaaba after God revealed its location to Abraham (peace be upon him). God Almighty says: {And [remember] when We assigned to Abraham the site of the House, [saying], "Do not associate anything with Me and purify My House for those who perform Tawaf and those who stand [in prayer] and those who bow and prostrate [in prayer]."} (26) (Surah Al-Hajj, verse 26).rnrnThus, God Almighty commanded Abraham (peace be upon him) to build the Sacred House. The Holy Quran mentions the building of the Kaaba by Prophet Abraham and his son Ishmael (peace be upon them both) and the purification of the surrounding area. The angel Gabriel (peace be upon him) brought the Black Stone to Abraham (peace be upon him). Initially, it was not black but rather a brilliant white, as the Prophet Muhammad (peace and blessings be upon him) said, “The Black Stone is from Paradise and was whiter than snow until the sins of the polytheists blackened it.”rnrnIt remained as it was until it was rebuilt by the Quraysh during the pre-Islamic era, about thirty years after the Year of the Elephant, following a great fire at the Kaaba. This fire was caused by a Quraysh woman attempting to fumigate the Kaaba, which ignited and weakened the structure. A flood then came and damaged parts of the Kaaba. The Quraysh rebuilt it, and the Prophet Muhammad, who was 35 years old at the time, was present and personally participated in the work alongside his uncles. When the Quraysh wanted to raise the Black Stone to its place during this rebuilding, they argued amongst themselves, to the point of near-war. They eventually agreed that the first man to emerge from their quarter would judge between them. The Messenger of God was the first to emerge, and he ruled that the Black Stone should be placed in a cloth (or covering) and then lifted by the tribal leaders. They lifted it, and then Muhammad, peace be upon him, ascended and placed it in its place with his own blessed hand. It should also be noted that Qusayy ibn Kilab, one of the Prophet Muhammad's ancestors, was the first to roof the Kaaba, using palm wood and palm fronds, before the Quraysh rebuilt it. For the Kaaba, a long time ago.',1,'2026-01-31 20:14:18.072317','2026-02-03 01:48:30.595840',NULL,NULL,NULL,13,'المَسْجِدُ الحَرَام هو أعظم مسجد في الإسلام ويقع في قلب مدينة مكة غرب المملكة العربية السعودية، تتوسطه الكعبة المشرفة التي هي أول بيت وضع للناس على وجه الأرض ليعبدوا الله فيه تبعاً للعقيدة الإسلامية، وهذه هي أعظم وأقدس بقعة على وجه الأرض عند المسلمين. والمسجد الحرام هو قبلة المسلمين في صلاتهم، وإليه يحجون. سمي بالمسجد الحرام لحرمة القتال فيه منذ دخول النبي محمد إلى مكة المكرمة منتصراً. ويؤمن المسلمون أن الصلاة فيه تعادل مئة ألف صلاة.','The Grand Mosque (Masjid al-Haram) is the holiest mosque in Islam, located in the heart of Mecca, in western Saudi Arabia. At its center stands the Kaaba, which, according to Islamic belief, is the first house of worship built for humanity on Earth. This is the most sacred and revered place on Earth for Muslims. The Grand Mosque is the direction Muslims face in prayer (qibla), and it is the destination of the Hajj pilgrimage. It is called the Grand Mosque because fighting within its precincts has been forbidden since the Prophet Muhammad's triumphant entry into Mecca. Muslims believe that a single prayer performed there is equivalent to one hundred thousand prayers elsewhere.','La Grande Mosquée (Masjid al-Haram) est le lieu de culte le plus sacré de l'islam. Située au cœur de La Mecque, dans l'ouest de l'Arabie saoudite, elle abrite en son centre la Kaaba, premier lieu de culte construit pour l'humanité selon la tradition islamique. C'est l'endroit le plus sacré et vénéré au monde pour les musulmans. La Grande Mosquée est la direction vers laquelle les musulmans se tournent pour prier (qibla) et le but du pèlerinage du Hajj. Elle est appelée ainsi car les combats y sont interdits depuis l'entrée triomphale du prophète Mahomet à La Mecque. Les musulmans croient qu'une seule prière accomplie en la Grande Mosquée équivaut à cent mille prières accomplies ailleurs.','مرحلة تشييد الكعبةrnيبدأ تاريخ المسجد بتاريخ بناء الكعبة المشرفة، وقد بناها أول مرة الملائكة قبل آدم عليه السلام، وكانت من ياقوتة حمراء، ثم رفع ذلك البناء إلى السماء أيام الطوفان، وبعد الطوفان قام النبي إبراهيم مع ابنه إسماعيل عليهما السلام، بإعادة بناء الكعبة، بعد أن أوحى الله إلى إبراهيم عليه السلام بمكان البيت، قال تعالى: ﴿وَإِذْ بَوَّأْنَا لِإِبْرَاهِيمَ مَكَانَ الْبَيْتِ أَنْ لَا تُشْرِكْ بِي شَيْئًا وَطَهِّرْ بَيْتِيَ لِلطَّائِفِينَ وَالْقَائِمِينَ وَالرُّكَّعِ السُّجُودِ ٢٦﴾(2) (سورة الحج الآية 26).rnrnوهـكذا أمر الله سبحانه وتعالى إبراهيم عليه السلام ببناء البيت الحرام. وذكر القرآن الكريم بناء سيدنا إبراهيم وابنه إسماعيل عليهما السلام للكعبة وتطهير المساحة المحيطة به، ولقد جاءه (أي إبراهيم عليه السلام) جبريل عليه السلام بالحجر الأسود، ولم يكن في بادئ الأمر أسود بل كان أَبْيَضَا يتلألأ من شدة البياض وذلك لقول الرسول ﷺ «الحجر الأسود من الجنة وكان أشد بياضا من الثلج حتى سودته خطايا أهل الشرك».rnrnوبقيت على حالها إلى أن تم إعادة بنائها على يد قريش في الجاهلية، بعد عام الفيل بحوالي ثلاثين عاماً بعد أن حدث حريق كبير بالكعبة، نتج عن محاولة امرأة من قريش تبخير الكعبة فاشتعلت النار وضعف البناء، ثم جاء سيل حطم أجزاء الكعبة، فأعادت قريش بناء الكعبة، وقد حضره النبي، وكان يبلغ من العمر حينها 35 سنة وشارك بنفسه الشريفة أعمامه في العمل، ولما أرادت قريش في هذا البناء أن ترفع الحجر الأسود لتضعه في مكانه اختصمت فيما بينها، حتى كانت تقع الحرب، ثم اصطلحوا على أن يحكم بينهم أول رجل يخرج من عليهم من هذه السكة، فكان رسول الله أول من خرج فقضى بينهم أن يجعلوا الحجر الأسود في مرط (أي كساء) ثم يرفعه زعماء القبائل فرفعوه ثم ارتقى محمد عليه السلام فوضعه بيده الشريفة مكانه، ويجب أن نشير أيضا أن قصي بن كلاب وهو أحد أجداد الرسول محمد أول من سَقْف الكعبة، حيث قام بسقفها بخشب الدوم وجريد النخيل، وذلك قبل بناء قريش للكعبة بزمن طويل.','The Construction of the KaabarnrnThe history of the mosque begins with the construction of the Holy Kaaba. It was first built by angels before Adam (peace be upon him), and it was made of red ruby. This structure was then raised to heaven during the Flood. After the Flood, the Prophet Abraham and his son Ishmael (peace be upon them both) rebuilt the Kaaba after God revealed its location to Abraham (peace be upon him). God Almighty says: {And [remember] when We assigned to Abraham the site of the House, [saying], "Do not associate anything with Me and purify My House for those who perform Tawaf and those who stand [in prayer] and those who bow and prostrate [in prayer]."} (26) (Surah Al-Hajj, verse 26).rnrnThus, God Almighty commanded Abraham (peace be upon him) to build the Sacred House. The Holy Quran mentions the building of the Kaaba by Prophet Abraham and his son Ishmael (peace be upon them both) and the purification of the surrounding area. The angel Gabriel (peace be upon him) brought the Black Stone to Abraham (peace be upon him). Initially, it was not black but rather a brilliant white, as the Prophet Muhammad (peace and blessings be upon him) said, “The Black Stone is from Paradise and was whiter than snow until the sins of the polytheists blackened it.”rnrnIt remained as it was until it was rebuilt by the Quraysh during the pre-Islamic era, about thirty years after the Year of the Elephant, following a great fire at the Kaaba. This fire was caused by a Quraysh woman attempting to fumigate the Kaaba, which ignited and weakened the structure. A flood then came and damaged parts of the Kaaba. The Quraysh rebuilt it, and the Prophet Muhammad, who was 35 years old at the time, was present and personally participated in the work alongside his uncles. When the Quraysh wanted to raise the Black Stone to its place during this rebuilding, they argued amongst themselves, to the point of near-war. They eventually agreed that the first man to emerge from their quarter would judge between them. The Messenger of God was the first to emerge, and he ruled that the Black Stone should be placed in a cloth (or covering) and then lifted by the tribal leaders. They lifted it, and then Muhammad, peace be upon him, ascended and placed it in its place with his own blessed hand. It should also be noted that Qusayy ibn Kilab, one of the Prophet Muhammad's ancestors, was the first to roof the Kaaba, using palm wood and palm fronds, before the Quraysh rebuilt it. For the Kaaba, a long time ago.','La construction de la KaabarnrnL'histoire de la mosquée commence avec la construction de la Sainte Kaaba. Elle fut d'abord érigée par des anges avant Adam (que la paix soit sur lui), et faite de rubis rouge. Cette structure fut ensuite élevée au ciel lors du Déluge. Après le Déluge, le prophète Abraham et son fils Ismaël (que la paix soit sur eux deux) reconstruisirent la Kaaba après que Dieu en eut révélé l'emplacement à Abraham (que la paix soit sur lui). Dieu Tout-Puissant dit : « Et [rappelez-vous] lorsque Nous avons assigné à Abraham l'emplacement de la Maison, [en disant] : « Ne M'associe rien et purifie Ma Maison pour ceux qui accomplissent le Tawaf, ceux qui se tiennent debout [en prière] et ceux qui s'inclinent et se prosternent [en prière]. » (26) (Sourate Al-Hajj, verset 26).rnrnAinsi, Dieu Tout-Puissant ordonna à Abraham (que la paix soit sur lui) de construire la Maison Sacrée. Le Saint Coran mentionne la construction de la Kaaba par le prophète Abraham et son fils Ismaël (que la paix soit sur eux) et la purification des environs. L'ange Gabriel (que la paix soit sur lui) apporta la Pierre Noire à Abraham (que la paix soit sur lui). À l'origine, elle n'était pas noire, mais d'un blanc éclatant, comme l'a dit le prophète Mohammed (que la paix et les bénédictions soient sur lui) : « La Pierre Noire vient du Paradis et était plus blanche que la neige jusqu'à ce que les péchés des polythéistes la noircissent. »rnrnElle demeura ainsi jusqu'à sa reconstruction par les Qurayshites à l'époque préislamique, environ trente ans après l'Année de l'Éléphant, suite à un grand incendie. Cet incendie fut provoqué par une femme qurayshite qui tentait de désinfecter la Kaaba, ce qui enflamma et fragilisa la structure. Une inondation survint ensuite et endommagea des parties de la Kaaba. Les Qurayshites la reconstruisirent, et le prophète Mohammed, alors âgé de 35 ans, était présent et participa personnellement aux travaux aux côtés de ses oncles. Lors de la reconstruction de la Kaaba, les Qurayshites voulurent la remettre à sa place. Des querelles éclatèrent entre eux, frôlant la guerre. Ils finirent par convenir que le premier homme qui se présenterait de leur quartier trancherait. Le Messager de Dieu fut le premier à apparaître et décréta que la Pierre Noire devait être placée dans un tissu (ou une couverture) puis soulevée par les chefs tribaux. Ils s'exécutèrent, puis Muhammad (que la paix soit sur lui) monta et la remit en place de sa propre main bénie. Il convient également de noter que Qusayy ibn Kilab, un ancêtre du Prophète Muhammad, fut le premier à couvrir la Kaaba, utilisant du bois et des palmes de palmier, avant sa reconstruction par les Qurayshites. Quant à la Kaaba, cela remonte à bien longtemps.');
